00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:05.840
Modern art helps us understand not only the artist, but also, ourselves. This video is

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:17.340
called Art &amp; Identity, a theme will explore
using three works. Since their marriage in

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:24.189
1929, Diego Rivera and Frida Kahlo had been
Mexico's most well-known couple. While Diego

00:00:24.189 --> 00:00:28.980
was a painter who was famous for his large
murals, Frida was a painter who was famous

00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:37.340
for being his wife. But in 1938, Frida's paintings
were starting to get attention. So she takes

00:00:37.340 --> 00:00:43.580
her first solo trip abroad. She has her first
solo shows in Paris and London. Her style

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:48.100
was unique.Was it Mexican Folk Art? was it
Surrealism? When asked, Frida simply said:

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:53.690
I paint my own reality. Picasso gives her
earrings. The Louvre buys a painting. Both

00:00:53.690 --> 00:00:59.280
shows are a success. She returns home, divorces
Diego Rivera and paints "Self-Portrait with

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:03.960
Cropped Hair." Her art had always been in
response to her life. I would imagine that

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:08.780
it would be a process that was sometimes very
hard for her. She used her artistic process

00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:16.250
as sort of an outlet. She marries her love
Diego Rivera and she paints this. She divorces

00:01:16.250 --> 00:01:21.600
her love Diego Rivera and she paints this.
She was determined not to simply be the ex

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:27.829
Mrs. Rivera. Diego had loved her long hair
and her colorful dresses. Frida painted herself

00:01:27.829 --> 00:01:32.799
without either. She's seated in this chair
with a pair of shears in one hand and a piece

00:01:32.799 --> 00:01:38.799
of her long hair in the other. She seemed
to reveal a lot about herself as an artist.

00:01:38.799 --> 00:01:47.569
She was willing to kind of go to those places
that not everybody is willing to go. In 1940,

00:01:47.569 --> 00:01:56.380
this is how Frida saw herself. In 1993, Glenn
Ligon asked ten friends how they saw him.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:02:00.609
